English\n|[[Lucie Jones]]\n|\"[[Never Give Up on You]]\"\n|align=center|15\n|align=center|111\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2018}}\n|English\n|[[SuRie]]\n|\"[[Storm (SuRie song)|Storm]]\"\n|align=center|24\n|align=center|48\n|-style=\"background:#fe8080;\"\n!{{Escyr|2019}}\n|English\n|[[Michael Rice (singer)|Michael Rice]]\n|\"[[Bigger than Us (Michael Rice song)|Bigger than Us]]\"\n|align=center|26 \u25c1\n|align=center|11\n|-bgcolor=\"#A4EAA9\"\n|{{N/A|{{Escyr|2020}}}}{{Efn|2020 contest was cancelled due to 2019-20 pandemic of Coronavirus.}}\n|English\n|[[James Newman (musician)|James Newman]]\n|\"[[My Last Breath]]\"\n|colspan=\"2\" {{N/A|Cancelled}}\n|}\n\n===Congratulations: 50 Years of the Eurovision Song Contest===\n{{further|Congratulations: 50 Years of the Eurovision Song Contest}}\n\nAlthough the United Kingdom was entered twice into ''[[Congratulations: 50 Years of the Eurovision Song Contest]]'', with [[Cliff Richard]]'s 1968 runner-up entry \"[[Congratulations (Cliff Richard song)|Congratulations]]\" and [[Brotherhood of Man]]'s 1976 winning song \"[[Save Your Kisses for Me]]\", the [[BBC]] decided not to air the event or participate in the voting, but instead aired an hour-long special programme entitled ''[[Boom Bang-a-Bang: 50 Years of Eurovision]]'' hosted by [[Terry Wogan]].\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%; text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Artist\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Language\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Title\n!colspan=\"4\"|At Congratulations\n!colspan=\"3\"|At Eurovision\n|-\n! width=\"50\" |Final\n! width=\"50\" |Points\n! width=\"50\" |Semi\n! width=\"50\" |Points\n! width=\"50\" |Year\n! width=\"50\" |Place\n! width=\"50\" |Points\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Cliff Richard]]\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[English language|English]]\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"[[Congratulations (Cliff Richard song)|Congratulations]]\"\n|colspan=\"2\" {{N/A|Failed to qualify}}\n|8\n|105\n|style=\"background:silver;\"|{{Escyr|1968}}\n|style=\"background:silver;\"|2\n|style=\"background:silver;\"|28\n|- \n|style=\"background:#fe8080;text-align:left;\"|[[Brotherhood of Man]]\n|style=\"background:#fe8080;text-align:left;\"|[[English language|English]]\n|style=\"background:#fe8080;text-align:left;\"|\"[[Save Your Kisses for Me]]\"\n|style=\"background:#fe8080;\"|5 \u25c1\n|style=\"background:#fe8080;\"|230\n|5\n|154\n|bgcolor=\"gold\"|{{Escyr|1976}}\n|bgcolor=\"gold\"|1\n|bgcolor=\"gold\"|164\n|}\n\n==Hostings==\nThe United Kingdom has hosted the Eurovision Song Contest a record eight times. The United Kingdom stepped in and hosted the contest for the {{Esccnty|Netherlands}} in {{Escyr|1960}}, {{Esccnty|France}} in {{Escyr|1963}}, {{Esccnty|Monaco}} in {{Escyr|1972}} and {{Esccnty|Luxembourg}} in {{Escyr|1974}} due to the winning countries' financial and capacity issues. In four occasions (1968, 1977, 1982 and 1998) the UK was given the right to host as a result of a victory. The [[BBC]] offered to joint host the {{Escyr|1996}} contest in [[Belfast]], [[Northern Ireland]] with Irish broadcaster [[RT\u00c9]] if {{Esccnty|Ireland}} were to win for a fourth year in a row.{{Citation needed|date=April 2014}}\n\n<!-- DO NOT add flagicons to the host city column.  This article is already about the United Kingdom, so there is no need to highlight with {{flagicon}} that the city is in the United Kingdom. This is in accordance with [[WP:ICONDECORATION]]. -->\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Location\n!Venue\n!Presenters\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1960}}\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[London]]\n|[[Royal Festival Hall]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Katie Boyle]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1963}}\n|[[BBC Television Centre]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1968}}\n|[[Royal Albert Hall]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1972}}\n|[[Edinburgh]]\n|[[Usher Hall]]\n|[[Moira Shearer]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1974}}\n|[[Brighton]]\n|[[Brighton Dome]]\n|[[Katie Boyle]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1977}}\n|[[London]]\n|[[Wembley Conference Centre]]\n|[[Angela Rippon]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1982}}\n|[[Harrogate]]\n|[[Harrogate International Centre]]\n|[[Jan Leeming]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1998}}\n|[[Birmingham]]\n|[[National Indoor Arena]]\n|[[Ulrika Jonsson]] and [[Terry Wogan]]\n|}\n\n===Eurovision Song Contest's Greatest Hits===\nIn 2015, [[London]] hosted ''[[Eurovision Song Contest's Greatest Hits]]'', an event to commemorate the 60th anniversary, which was recorded for television on 31 March 2015 and was shown in 26 countries, starting with the UK and Ireland on 3 April 2015.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Roxburgh|first1=Gordon|title=Official: London to host Eurovision's 60th anniversary event|url=http://www.eurovision.tv/page/news?id=official_london_to_host_eurovisions_60th_anniversary_event|website=eurovision.tv|publisher=European Broadcasting Union|accessdate=3 February 2015|date=3 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|- \n!Year\n!Location\n!Venue\n!Presenters\n!Image\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[Eurovision Song Contest's Greatest Hits|2015]]\n|[[London]]\n|[[Eventim Apollo]]\n|[[Petra Mede]] and [[Graham Norton]]\n|[[File:Hosts of the Eurovision Greatest Hits.jpg|150px]]\n|}\n\n==''Eurovision: Come Together''==\nOn 24 March 2020, the BBC announced that [[BBC Studios]] would produce a replacement show for BBC One featuring classic Eurovision performances, interviews and a look at the entries that would have took part in 2020. ''Eurovision: Come Together'' is part of the BBC\u2019s plan to \"entertain the nation in time of need\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2020/bbc-entertains-the-nation-in-time-of-need|title=BBC - BBC entertains the nation in time of need - Media Centre|website=www.bbc.co.uk|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n===AP Awards===\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Category\n!Song\n!Performer(s)\n!style=\"width:45px;\"|Place\n!style=\"width:45px;\"|Points\n!Host city\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2004}}\n|Composer Award\n|\"[[Hold Onto Our Love]]\"\n|[[James Fox (singer)|James Fox]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|16\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|29\n|{{flagicon|Turkey}} [[Istanbul]]\n|}\n\n==Related involvement==\n===Heads of delegation===\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n!Year\n!Head of delegation\n!{{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2012}}\n|Andrew Cartmell\n|{{center|<ref name=\"cartmell\">{{cite web|url=https://eurovoix.com/2018/12/02/united-kingdom-andrew-cartmell-revealed-as-head-of-delegation/|title=United Kingdom: Andrew Cartmell Revealed as Head of Delegation|website=eurovoix.com|date=2 December 2018|accessdate=5 December 2019|first=Anthony|last=Granger}}</ref>}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2014}}\u2013{{Escyr|2017}}\n|Guy Freeman\n|{{center|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://esctoday.com/156242/united-kingdom-head-delegation-guy-freeman-leave-bbc-next-month/|title=United Kingdom: Head of Delegation Guy Freeman to leave BBC next month|date=13 January 2018|accessdate=7 December 2019|website=esctoday.com|first=Jessica|last=Weaver}}</ref>}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2018}}\n|Helen Riddell\n|{{center|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovoix.com/2018/10/24/united-kingdom-helen-riddell-steps-down-as-head-of-delegation/|title=United Kingdom: Helen Riddell Steps Down as Head of Delegation|website=eurovoix.com|date=24 October 2018|accessdate=5 December 2019|first=Neil|last=Farren}}</ref>}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2019}}\n|Andrew Cartmell\n|{{center|<ref name=\"cartmell\"/>}}\n|}\n\n===Commentators and spokespersons===\n{{more citations needed section|date=January 2020}}\nOver the years BBC commentary has been provided by several experienced radio and television presenters, including [[Tom Fleming (actor)|Tom Fleming]], [[David Vine]], [[David Jacobs (broadcaster)|David Jacobs]], [[Dave Lee Travis]], [[Pete Murray (disc jockey)|Pete Murray]], [[John Dunn (radio presenter)|John Dunn]] and [[Michael Aspel]]. However, Terry Wogan provided BBC TV commentary every year from 1980 to 2008.<ref>[http://eurovisionarchive.members.beeb.net/trivia.htm Trivia] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509081131/http://eurovisionarchive.members.beeb.net/trivia.htm|date=May 9, 2008}}</ref> It was confirmed on 12 August 2008 that [[Terry Wogan]] would no longer present the [[Eurovision Song Contest]] for the UK. The [[BBC Radio 2]] DJ, who had fronted the BBC's coverage for 37 years, said it was \"time for someone else to take over\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/a121932/terry-wogan-quits-eurovision-role.html |title=Terry Wogan quits Eurovision role |website=Digital Spy|author=Fletcher, Alex |date=2008-08-12 |accessdate=2008-08-12}}</ref> He was replaced in 2009 by [[Graham Norton]] for the final. Norton has continued in the role ever since.\n\nThe final of the contest has been broadcast by [[BBC One]] (previously BBC Television Service and BBC TV) since the first contest in 1956, the first live colour transmission of the contest in the United Kingdom was the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1970]], the first high definition broadcast of the contest began in 2007 when the contest was simulcast on [[BBC HD]]. The final is also broadcast on radio, initially on [[BBC Light Programme]] until the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1967|1967 contest]]. From 1968 it was broadcast on [[BBC Radio 1]] (simulcast on Radio 2), moving to [[BBC Radio 2]] from the 1971 contest where it has remained ever since (except for 1983\u20131985).  Between 1963 and 1976 and from 1980 until 1985 the contest was also broadcast on [[British Forces Broadcasting Service|BFBS Radio]]. From 2004 to 2015 both semi-finals were broadcast on [[BBC Three]]. Since BBC Three became an online only channel in February 2016, semi-final coverage is now broadcast on [[BBC Four]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.a516digital.com/2016/01/bbc-four-takes-over-eurovision-coverage.html|title=BBC Four takes over Eurovision coverage|publisher=a516digital.com|date=17 January 2016|accessdate=25 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the {{Escyr|1998}} contest, hosted in Birmingham, Terry Wogan acted as both commentator and on-stage presenter (together with [[Ulrika Jonsson]]). In the {{Escyr|1980}} contest, each song was introduced by a presenter from its country, the United Kingdom entry being introduced by [[Noel Edmonds]].\n\nNo British-born broadcaster has either presented or commentated on the live television final for over thirty years, the last being [[Jan Leeming]], host of the {{Escyr|1982}} contest.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n!rowspan=\"2\" |Year\n!colspan=\"2\" |Television commentator\n!rowspan=\"2\" |Radio commentator\n!rowspan=\"2\" |Online/BFBS commentator\n!rowspan=\"2\" |Spokesperson\n!rowspan=\"2\" class=\"unsortable\"|{{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n!Final\n!Semi-final\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1956}}\n|[[Wilfrid Thomas]]||rowspan=\"48\" {{N/A|No semi-finals}} ||Unknown ||rowspan=\"8\" {{N/A}}||{{N/A|Did not participate}} ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1957}}\n|[[Berkeley Smith]] ||rowspan=\"2\"|[[Tom Sloan (television executive)|Tom Sloan]] ||[[David Jacobs (broadcaster)|David Jacobs]]  ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1958}}\n|[[Peter Haigh]] ||{{N/A|Did not participate}} ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1959}}\n|Tom Sloan || rowspan=\"3\" |[[Pete Murray (DJ)|Pete Murray]] || Pete Murray ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1960}}\n|David Jacobs ||{{nowrap|Nick Burrell-Davis}} ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1961}}\n|Tom Sloan ||[[Michael Aspel]] ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1962}}\n|rowspan=\"5\"|David Jacobs ||Peter Haigh ||[[Alex Macintosh]] ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1963}}\n|Michael Aspel ||Pete Murray ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1964}}\n|Tom Sloan || rowspan=\"3\" |Ian Fenner||[[Kenneth Kendall]] ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1965}}\n|[[David Gell]] ||[[Alastair Burnet]] ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1966}}\n|[[John Dunn (radio presenter)|John Dunn]] ||rowspan =\"3\"|Michael Aspel ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1967}}\n|[[Rolf Harris]] ||[[Richard Baker (broadcaster)|Richard Baker]] ||rowspan=\"2\"|{{nowrap|Thurston Holland}} ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1968}}\n|{{N/A}} ||rowspan=\"2\"|Pete Murray ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1969}}\n|David Gell, Michael Aspel || rowspan=\"3\" |John Russell||rowspan=\"2\" |Colin-Ward Lewis ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1970}}\n|David Gell ||[[Tony Brandon]] ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1971}}\n|[[Dave Lee Travis]] ||[[Terry Wogan]] ||rowspan=\"3\" {{N/A}} ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1972}}\n|[[Tom Fleming (actor)|Tom Fleming]] ||rowspan=\"2\"|Pete Murray ||Terry James ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1973}}\n|Terry Wogan || rowspan=\"4\" |{{nowrap|Richard Astbury}}{{Efn|It has to be assumed that Terry Wogan's commentary was taken by BFBS in 1975 since Terry says in his BBC Radio 2 commentary \"Richard Astbury sends his apologies to BFBS listeners - technical difficulties\".}} ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1974}}\n|[[David Vine]] ||rowspan=\"4\"|Terry Wogan ||Colin-Ward Lewis ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1975}}\n|Pete Murray || rowspan=\"2\" |[[Ray Moore (broadcaster)|Ray Moore]] ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1976}}\n|Michael Aspel ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1977}}\n|Pete Murray ||rowspan=\"3\" {{N/A}}||rowspan=\"3\" |[[Colin Berry]] ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1978}}\n|Terry Wogan || rowspan=\"2\" |Ray Moore ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1979}}\n|John Dunn ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1980}}\n|rowspan=\"29\"|Terry Wogan ||[[Steve Jones (game show presenter)|Steve Jones]] ||Andrew Pastona||Ray Moore ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1981}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Ray Moore ||rowspan=\"2\" {{N/A}}||rowspan=\"17\" |Colin Berry ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1982}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1983}}\n|rowspan=\"3\" {{N/A|Not broadcast on BBC Radio}} ||rowspan=\"3\"|{{nowrap|Richard Nankivell}} ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1984}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|